---
description: Code quality standards - naming, organization, docs, security, process
alwaysApply: true
---

## CODE QUALITY
- Explicit over clever — readable beats smart every time
- Early returns and guard clauses — avoid deeply nested conditionals
- Handle errors at the start of functions, happy path goes last
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, or credentials — always use env vars
- DRY — flag repetition aggressively before implementing
- No dead code — remove unused variables, functions, and imports
- Bias toward handling more edge cases, not fewer
- Avoid magic numbers and strings — use named constants or configuration

## NAMING
- Prefer clear, intention-revealing names over implementation details.
- Avoid single-letter names except for trivial loop/index variables.
- Boolean identifiers should read like questions: `is`, `has`, `can`, or `should` prefixes.
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE or language-idiomatic constant style
- Functions: verb + noun (e.g. `fetchUser`, `validateInput`, `sendEmail`)
- Keep exported/public names stable; refactors should prefer adding new exports and deprecating old ones over renaming.

## CODE ORGANIZATION
- Reuse existing patterns and utilities before introducing new abstractions.
- Keep modules focused: one reason to change per file/class/function.
- Place “boundary” logic (parsing/validation/authorization) as close to inputs/edges as possible; keep core logic side-effect-light.
- Keep error handling near the start of functions; prefer guard clauses over deep nesting.

## DOCUMENTATION
- Document public APIs (exported functions/classes, new endpoints) with: purpose, parameters, return value, and notable side effects.
- Prefer small, targeted comments for “why” or constraints; avoid comments that only restate code.
- Keep comments up to date when behavior changes — delete obsolete comments
- Never add comments that just restate what the code does
- For non-trivial flows (data pipelines, state machines, error flows), prefer ASCII diagrams in the plan or nearby code comments so future changes don’t break assumptions.

## SECURITY
- Secrets never in code — .env only, never committed to git
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs at boundaries
- Principle of least privilege on all permissions
- Dependency hygiene — flag outdated or vulnerable packages when spotted

## GIT / PROCESS
- Commit messages: conventional commits format (feat:, fix:, chore:, docs:, refactor:)
- Never commit directly to main
- Run tests before suggesting a commit
- Keep commits atomic — one logical change per commit
- No “drive-by cleanups”: only change what is needed for the requested behavior.
- If you add a new TODO, follow the `TODOS.md` format and include enough context to resume later without guessing.